-- 14-dependency-graph-builder.cell (v0.2)
-- Tests: recursive graph construction, ‚äĘ‚äĘ spawner (accumulate), structural oracle
--        (acyclicity), internal vs external dependency classification, DAG validation,
--        wildcard deps, guard clauses, file-scope ‚ä®?
--
-- v0.2 changes from R16:
--   - Added file-scope ‚ä®? recovery policy (retry max 2, then error-value(‚ä•))
--   - Wildcard deps (analyzer-*‚Üífield, sub-analyzer-*‚Üífield) now formally v0.2 compliant
--   - ‚äĘ‚äĘ spawners: explicit `accumulate` mode (default, but stated for clarity)
--   - Guard clause on handle-cycle / handle-acyclic for conditional dispatch
--   - given? on assemble-full-graph for ‚ä•-tolerant sub-analyzer wildcard
--   - Oracles on ‚äĘ‚ąė-managed cells (dependency-analyzer-template) are aspirational
--   - ‚äĘ‚ąė refine-graph added: iterates sub-module analysis through consistency check
--
-- Takes a codebase description. Identifies modules. For each module, identifies
-- dependencies. For each internal dependency, recurses into sub-modules.
-- Builds a complete DAG. Oracle validates: is the DAG acyclic?
--
-- Codebase: Gas Town ‚ÄĒ a multi-agent workspace manager
--   mayor (coordinator), witness (polecat lifecycle), refinery (merge queue),
--   beads (issue tracking), gt CLI (orchestration), dolt (data layer)

‚ä®? on failure:
  retry with ¬ęoracle.failures¬Ľ appended to prompt
  max 2 attempts
‚ä®? on exhaustion:
  error-value(‚ä•)

‚äĘ codebase
  given description ‚Č° "Gas Town ‚ÄĒ a multi-agent workspace manager with: mayor (coordinator that dispatches work and handles escalations), witness (monitors polecat lifecycle, health checks, nudges stuck agents), refinery (bisecting merge queue that merges polecat branches), beads (Dolt-backed issue tracking with dependency DAG), gt CLI (orchestration commands: prime, hook, done, mail, escalate), dolt (SQL data layer providing versioned database for beads and agent state)"
  yield description

  ‚ä® description names at least 4 distinct modules

‚äĘ identify-modules
  given codebase‚Üídescription
  yield modules[], module-descriptions[]

  ‚ąī Read ¬ęcodebase‚Üídescription¬Ľ and identify all top-level modules.
    For each module, provide a one-line description of its responsibility.
    Include only modules that are part of Gas Town itself (internal),
    not external dependencies like Go stdlib or third-party libraries.

  ‚ä® length(modules) ‚Č• 4
  ‚ä® each module has a clear single responsibility
  ‚ä® modules are non-overlapping

‚äĘ‚äĘ spawn-dependency-analyzers
  given identify-modules‚Üímodules
  given identify-modules‚Üímodule-descriptions
  given ¬ßdependency-analyzer-template
  yield ¬ßanalyzer-cells[]
  until length(analyzer-cells) = length(identify-modules‚Üímodules)
  max 10
  accumulate

  ‚ąī For each module in ¬ęidentify-modules‚Üímodules¬Ľ, spawn a cell that
    identifies what other modules it depends on and classifies each
    dependency as internal (within Gas Town) or external.

  ‚ä® one analyzer cell per module

‚äĘ dependency-analyzer-template
  given module-name
  given module-desc
  given all-modules[]
  yield depends-on[], dependency-types[], rationale

  ‚ąī For module ¬ęmodule-name¬Ľ (¬ęmodule-desc¬Ľ), identify all modules it
    depends on. For each dependency:
    - Name the depended-on module
    - Classify as "internal" (in ¬ęall-modules¬Ľ) or "external"
    - Explain WHY the dependency exists (what service/data flows)

    Only include DIRECT dependencies (not transitive).

  ‚ä® each dependency is classified as "internal" or "external"
  ‚ä® no self-dependencies (module cannot depend on itself)
  ‚ä® rationale explains each dependency's purpose

‚äĘ build-adjacency
  given analyzer-*‚Üídepends-on
  given analyzer-*‚Üídependency-types
  given identify-modules‚Üímodules
  yield edges[], internal-edges[], external-deps[]

  ‚ąī Collect all dependency information from analyzer cells.
    Build the adjacency list:
    - edges: all (source, target) pairs
    - internal-edges: only edges where both source and target are internal modules
    - external-deps: external dependencies grouped by module

  ‚ä® every edge has a valid source and target
  ‚ä® internal-edges is a subset of edges
  ‚ä® no duplicate edges

‚äĘ validate-acyclicity
  given build-adjacency‚Üíinternal-edges
  given identify-modules‚Üímodules
  yield is-acyclic, topological-order[], cycle-description

  ‚ąī Check if the internal dependency graph is acyclic (a valid DAG).
    Use topological sort: if all nodes can be ordered such that every
    edge points from earlier to later in the order, the graph is acyclic.

    If acyclic: produce the topological ordering.
    If cyclic: describe the cycle (which modules form the loop).

  ‚ä® is-acyclic ‚ąą { true, false }
  ‚ä® if is-acyclic then topological-order contains all modules
  ‚ä® if not is-acyclic then cycle-description names the cycle

  ‚ä®? on failure:
    retry with ¬ęoracle.failures¬Ľ max 2

‚äĘ handle-acyclic
  given validate-acyclicity‚Üíis-acyclic where is-acyclic = true
  given validate-acyclicity‚Üítopological-order
  given identify-modules‚Üímodules
  yield dag-status, ordering-summary

  ‚ąī The internal dependency graph is acyclic. Summarize the topological
    ordering ¬ęvalidate-acyclicity‚Üítopological-order¬Ľ and explain what it
    reveals about the system's layering: which modules are foundational
    (no dependencies) and which are high-level (many dependencies).

  ‚ä® dag-status = "acyclic"
  ‚ä® ordering-summary references the topological order

‚äĘ handle-cycle
  given validate-acyclicity‚Üíis-acyclic where is-acyclic = false
  given validate-acyclicity‚Üícycle-description
  yield dag-status, cycle-analysis

  ‚ąī The internal dependency graph contains a cycle: ¬ęvalidate-acyclicity‚Üícycle-description¬Ľ.
    Analyze why this cycle exists and propose how to break it
    (which dependency should be inverted or removed).

  ‚ä® dag-status = "cyclic"
  ‚ä® cycle-analysis proposes at least one way to break the cycle

‚äĘ‚äĘ spawn-sub-module-analyzers
  given build-adjacency‚Üíinternal-edges
  given identify-modules‚Üímodules
  given ¬ßsub-module-analyzer-template
  yield ¬ßsub-analyzer-cells[]
  until length(sub-analyzer-cells) = length(identify-modules‚Üímodules)
  max 10
  accumulate

  ‚ąī For each internal module, spawn a cell that identifies its
    SUB-MODULES (internal components). This is the recursive step:
    each module is itself composed of sub-modules with their own
    internal dependency structure.

  ‚ä® one sub-analyzer cell per module

‚äĘ sub-module-analyzer-template
  given module-name
  given module-deps[]
  yield sub-modules[], sub-edges[], sub-is-acyclic

  ‚ąī Decompose ¬ęmodule-name¬Ľ into its internal sub-modules (2-4 components).
    Identify dependencies between sub-modules. Check acyclicity within
    this module.

  ‚ä® 2 ‚Č§ length(sub-modules) ‚Č§ 4
  ‚ä® sub-is-acyclic ‚ąą { true, false }
  ‚ä® sub-edges only reference sub-modules within this module

‚äĘ check-sub-consistency
  given sub-analyzer-*‚Üísub-modules
  given sub-analyzer-*‚Üísub-edges
  given sub-analyzer-*‚Üísub-is-acyclic
  given build-adjacency‚Üíinternal-edges
  yield all-sub-acyclic, cross-module-conflicts[], consistency-score

  ‚ąī Check consistency of sub-module decompositions:
    - Are all sub-module graphs individually acyclic?
    - Do cross-module edges (from ¬ębuild-adjacency‚Üíinternal-edges¬Ľ)
      plausibly map to sub-module-level connections?
    - Are there any contradictions between a module's sub-module structure
      and its declared dependencies?
    Assign a consistency score (0-10).

  ‚ä® all-sub-acyclic ‚ąą { true, false }
  ‚ä® consistency-score ‚ąą [0, 10]

‚äĘ‚ąė refine-graph(sub-module-analyzer-template)
  through check-sub-consistency
  until check-sub-consistency‚Üíconsistency-score ‚Č• 8
  max 2

  -- Each iteration: sub-module decompositions are re-evaluated with
  -- feedback from check-sub-consistency about conflicts and contradictions.
  -- The evolution loop rewrites the template's outputs with refined
  -- decompositions. Interface preserved; only sub-module assignments change.

‚äĘ assemble-full-graph
  given identify-modules‚Üímodules
  given build-adjacency‚Üíinternal-edges
  given build-adjacency‚Üíexternal-deps
  given validate-acyclicity‚Üíis-acyclic
  given validate-acyclicity‚Üítopological-order
  given? handle-acyclic‚Üíordering-summary
  given? handle-cycle‚Üícycle-analysis
  given sub-analyzer-*‚Üísub-modules
  given sub-analyzer-*‚Üísub-edges
  given sub-analyzer-*‚Üísub-is-acyclic
  given check-sub-consistency‚Üíconsistency-score
  yield full-dag, layer-count, total-nodes, total-edges, summary

  ‚ąī Assemble the complete two-level dependency graph:
    Level 1: module-to-module dependencies (top-level DAG)
    Level 2: sub-module dependencies within each module

    Present the graph as a structured DAG with:
    - Topological layer assignment (modules with no deps = layer 0)
    - Total node and edge counts (both levels combined)
    - Any cycles detected at either level
    - If ¬ęhandle-acyclic‚Üíordering-summary¬Ľ is available, incorporate it.
      If ¬ęhandle-cycle‚Üícycle-analysis¬Ľ is available, incorporate it.
      (Exactly one will be ‚ä• due to guard dispatch.)

  ‚ä® full-dag includes both levels
  ‚ä® layer-count ‚Č• 2
  ‚ä® summary describes the graph structure and any findings
